<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The starting situation</span>
<h2 class="h2">An award-winning niche DTC product, ready to scale</h2>
<p class="body"><strong>Company:</strong> The Stack System — an award-winning golf-speed-training product co-developed with PING's VP of Performance and golf's leading biomechanist. Real product credibility, real product-market fit with serious golfers.</p>
<p class="body"><strong>The constraint:</strong> Niche product, defensible technology, devoted early customer base — but the acquisition motion to scale beyond that base hadn't been built. Paid social had been tested; conversion rates were inconsistent; influencer partnerships were ad-hoc rather than systematized.</p>
<p class="body"><strong>What Treetop was asked to own:</strong> Customer acquisition. Paid social, paid search, creative testing, conversion optimization, and a systematized influencer partnership program.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">What we built</span>
<h2 class="h2">The acquisition system</h2>

<h3 class="h3">Paid social architecture (Meta)</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Top-of-funnel + retargeting blended campaigns.</strong> Disciplined separation of prospecting and retargeting audiences; creative tailored to funnel stage rather than reused across.</li>
<li><strong>Aggressive creative testing.</strong> Continuous variant testing across video, image, copy hooks, and product positioning. The wins compounded — most months had at least one new creative that outperformed the prior champion.</li>
<li><strong>Result: 20–36x ROAS on Meta ads</strong> (blended across top-of-funnel and retargeting). For a specialty DTC product with a strong product story, this is the upper end of what's achievable.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">Paid search</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Branded + non-branded coverage.</strong> Defensive on branded; aggressive on category and competitor terms.</li>
<li><strong>Landing page conversion optimization.</strong> The product story translated to paid-search landing pages — different surface, same conversion discipline.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">Influencer partnership program</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Pitched via Instagram DM, negotiated to evergreen contract.</strong> A single high-leverage influencer partnership that featured an evergreen content collaboration with product placement.</li>
<li><strong>200% ROI in 9 months.</strong> The structure (evergreen content + affiliate sales) means the partnership continues generating returns long after the initial contract period.</li>
<li><strong>Repeatable framework.</strong> Influencer outreach methodology, partnership terms, and creative collaboration model documented for future expansion of the program.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Results</span>
<h2 class="h2">What changed in 12 months</h2>
<div class="metric-grid">
<div class="metric-tile"><div class="metric-tile-num">+245%</div><div class="metric-tile-label">YoY revenue growth</div></div>
<div class="metric-tile"><div class="metric-tile-num">20–36×</div><div class="metric-tile-label">ROAS on Meta ads (blended)</div></div>
<div class="metric-tile"><div class="metric-tile-num">200%</div><div class="metric-tile-label">ROI on influencer partnership in 9 months</div></div>
<div class="metric-tile"><div class="metric-tile-num">Evergreen</div><div class="metric-tile-label">Affiliate revenue contracted to continue post-engagement</div></div>
</div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">What we'd tell you about this pattern</span>
<h2 class="h2">What worked, what this means for your stage</h2>

<h3 class="h3">What worked</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Specialty product + disciplined paid acquisition + influencer leverage.</strong> The combination ROAS ceiling for this product category was meaningfully higher than for commodity DTC — but only with creative discipline and audience separation. Most DTC operators leave 30-50% of achievable ROAS on the table by running blended campaigns instead of stage-separated ones.</li>
<li><strong>Influencer partnership as evergreen asset, not one-time spend.</strong> Most influencer deals are structured as one-time content drops. Structuring as evergreen with affiliate-sales tail produces dramatically better long-term ROI — and dramatically fewer relationships to manage.</li>
<li><strong>Creative testing as a discipline, not an event.</strong> The 20–36x ROAS range didn't show up in week one. It showed up in month 6 after continuous creative iteration. Operators who give up on paid social after 90 days of "it's not working" usually quit right before the creative system starts producing.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h3">If you're a specialty DTC product</h3>
<p class="body">This pattern — fractional growth leadership applied specifically to paid social + paid search + influencer-as-evergreen — fits specialty DTC products with real product credibility, defensible positioning, and a devoted early customer base. The leverage is in disciplined acquisition systems, not just spending more on ads. If your ROAS ceiling feels stuck, the answer is usually creative + audience architecture, not budget.</p>
</div></section>

